    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Invisible leaks, especially in resource-constrained environments, are often caused by subtle lifetime mismanagement or fragmentation, not just a single forgotten `delete`. It's less about a missing pointer and more about memory being held onto longer than necessary, or the heap itself becoming unusable.\n\nIf the simple counter tracking doesn't pinpoint the issue, you need to look at the *scope* of the objects. Are you using raw pointers (`SensorData*`) everywhere, or are you using smart pointers (like `std::unique_ptr`)? If you are using raw pointers, even if you delete the object, if another part of the system holds a stale reference, you might be dealing with a use-after-free or a memory corruption issue masquerading as a leak.\n\nConsider replacing raw pointers with `std::unique_ptr` for ownership transfer, even if you have to implement a lightweight version compatible with your embedded C++. This forces you to explicitly define who owns the memory, which is the primary defense against these subtle pointer-related vanishing acts. If the memory is being \"lost,\" it might be because the ownership chain was broken somewhere upstream.",
